15 WHEREAS, innovative programs and pathways to enter the teaching profession can attract
16 a diverse and talented pool of candidates and strengthen the education workforce; and
17 WHEREAS, supporting teacher retention through mentorship programs, professional
18 development, and enhanced working conditions can improve educator satisfaction and
19 student outcomes; and
20 WHEREAS, partnerships and collaboration between state and local education agencies,
21 local school systems, postsecondary educational institutions, and other stakeholders are
22 essential to addressing the complex challenges facing the education workforce.
23 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE that:
24 (1) The Professional Standards Commission is urged to lead a collaborative effort with
25 the Department of Education, the Department of Early Care and Learning, the Office of
26 Student Achievement, the University System of Georgia, the Technical College System
27 of Georgia, and the Georgia Student Finance Commission so as to provide the Governor
28 and the General Assembly with comprehensive recommendations to strengthen the K-12
29 education workforce;
30 (2) Such recommendations should address, but not be limited to, the following priorities:
31 (A) Encouraging innovative programs to enter the early childhood and K-12 teaching
32 profession, such as enhanced student teaching models, apprenticeship programs, and
33 "tutors to teachers" pathways;
34 (B) Collecting, reviewing, and providing data for the success of graduates employed
35 in the teaching profession in Georgia from all teacher education programs, both in state
36 and out of state, to include placement, effectiveness, and retention rates after one,
37 three, five, and ten years;
